<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ911119-0133</DOCNO><DOCID>911119-0133.</DOCID><HL>   Letters to the Editor:   Better Believe It</HL><DATE>11/19/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A21</SO><IN>ECONOMIC NEWS (ECO)</IN><GV>FEDERAL RESERVE BOARD (FED)</GV><RE>NORTH AMERICA (NME)UNITED STATES (US)</RE><LP>   One thing that might help &quot;economic experts&quot; make theconnection between their credit and consumers' confidenceindexes and Alan Greenspan's grimness (Oct. 29) is anawareness of the origin of the word &quot;credit.&quot; It stems fromthe Latin verb creder, meaning &quot;to believe in.&quot;   America's undeniable problem is not a lack of itscitizens' confidence in things they rightfully should be&quot;believing in,&quot; but a lack of things -- such as governments,banks, the legal system, insurance companies, ad nauseam --in which its citizens reasonably might be expected to place&quot;credence&quot; (another variation of creder).</LP><TEXT>   Robert P. O'Donnell   Las Vegas, Nev.</TEXT></DOC>